# Project 1 — KKBOX Churn Prediction

## The business problem
KKBOX is a music streaming app with 992,931 subscribers.
6.4% churn every month. Which users are about to cancel — and why?

## Dataset
- Source: WSDM KKBox Churn Prediction Challenge (Kaggle)
- Size: 8.6 GB across 4 files
- Users: 992,931 | Churners: 63,547

## Model
- Algorithm: XGBoost (300 trees, depth 6, learning rate 0.05)
- Features: 14 across 3 tiers — intent, behaviour, profile
- Train/test split: 80/20

## Results

| Metric | Target | Achieved | Status |
|--------|--------|---------|--------|
| AUC | 0.75–0.85 | **0.981** | PASS |
| F1 Score | 0.55–0.65 | **0.749** | PASS |

## Feature importance

| Rank | Feature | Importance | PM action |
|------|---------|-----------|-----------|
| 1 | days_until_expiry | 39.9% | Expiry countdown campaign |
| 2 | is_auto_renew | 35.4% | Auto-renew off alert |
| 3 | is_cancel | 18.8% | Cancellation flow redesign |
| 4–14 | All others | 6.1% | Low priority |

## The key finding
> KKBOX churn is a subscription mechanics problem, not an engagement problem.

Total listening time contributed less than 0.3% of predictive power.
Users leave because of billing friction — not because they stopped enjoying music.

This means: stop investing in recommendation algorithms to reduce churn.
Start investing in renewal UX, expiry notifications, and cancellation flow redesign.

## Product roadmap

| Priority | Feature | Trigger | Impact |
|---------|---------|---------|--------|
| P0 | Auto-renew off alert | User turns off auto-renew | Very High |
| P0 | Expiry countdown campaign | 14 days before expiry | Very High |
| P1 | Cancellation flow redesign | User initiates cancel | High |
| P2 | Price match on renewal | Discounted user renewing | Medium |

## Business impact
- 47,587 at-risk users correctly identified
- At $10 ARPU and 30% retention rate: **$142,000/month recoverable revenue**

